<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-086-015 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 071 171</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 5 1991 v25 n31 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sunamerica shredding costs with paper cuts. (creating a'paperless' office; includes related article on the objections togetting rid of paper files) (On Site)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sunamerica Corp leads in the move from paper to electronic filemanagement.andP;  It does this by willingly undertaking a completereview of how paper files are used and abused in its operations.andO;The financial services and insurance firm uses a combination ofgood planning and high technology to eliminate paper files fromits offices over a two-year period beginning in 1989.andP;  Thetechnology includes imaging systems, application software forrouting electronic documents, and computers, at a cost of $3.5million including customizing the software, but not including 120IBM PS/2 microcomputers.andP;  The effects of the move to a 'paperless'environment are improved response time to customer and field agentrequests, often from a day to a few seconds, and fewer staffneeded, with a reduction from 400 to 200 people.andP;  Sunamerica seemsto have taken the opportunity of automation not only to plan theconversion, but also to streamline its operations generally.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   SunAmerica Corp. (Automation).andO;Topic:     File managementInsurance IndustryAutomationElectronic Filing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>